<TITLE>Dystopian novels hit bestseller lists</TITLE>


<TEXT>
Heres food for thought. 
 
Dystopian tales, books most people havent read since high school, were <EVENT eid="e1" class="OCCURRENCE">sprinkled</EVENT> into Amazons Bestseller List of books <TIMEX3 tid="t1" type="DATE" value="2017-W05">this week</TIMEX3>. 
 
A book first <EVENT eid="e2" class="OCCURRENCE">published</EVENT> in 1949  George Orwells <TIMEX3 tid="t2" type="DATE" value="1984">1984</TIMEX3> shot to No. 1 on that list. 
 
Orwells dystopia  where all language and thought are controlled by the Party  has <EVENT eid="e3" class="OCCURRENCE">experienced</EVENT> enough of a resurgence that publisher Penguin <EVENT eid="e4" class="I_ACTION">ordered</EVENT> a 75,000-book reprint, according to CNN. 
 
If you recall from your high school English class, the books protagonist Winston Smiths job is to <EVENT eid="e5" class="OCCURRENCE">replace</EVENT> historical truths with new, state-approved facts. 
 
Orwell <EVENT eid="e6" class="REPORTING">wrote</EVENT>: 
 
Every record has been <EVENT eid="e7" class="OCCURRENCE">destroyed</EVENT> or <EVENT eid="e8" class="OCCURRENCE">falsified</EVENT>, every book <EVENT eid="e9" class="OCCURRENCE">rewritten</EVENT>, every picture has been <EVENT eid="e10" class="OCCURRENCE">repainted</EVENT>, every statue and street building has been <EVENT eid="e11" class="OCCURRENCE">renamed</EVENT>, every date has been <EVENT eid="e12" class="OCCURRENCE">altered</EVENT>. And the process is <EVENT eid="e13" class="ASPECTUAL">continuing</EVENT> <TIMEX3 tid="t3" type="DURATION" value="PXD">day</TIMEX3> by <TIMEX3 tid="t4" type="DURATION" value="PXD">day</TIMEX3> and <TIMEX3 tid="t5" type="DATE" value="X">minute</TIMEX3> by <TIMEX3 tid="t6" type="DATE" value="X">minute</TIMEX3>. History has <EVENT eid="e14" class="OCCURRENCE">stopped</EVENT>. Nothing exists except an endless present in which the Party is always right. 
 
In Orwells dystopia, where language is <EVENT eid="e15" class="OCCURRENCE">changed</EVENT> into the Partys Newspeak  and a Party slogan is Ignorance is Strength  the first primary means of thought control is Crimestop. He <EVENT eid="e16" class="OCCURRENCE">writes</EVENT>: 
 
Crimestop means the faculty of <EVENT eid="e17" class="OCCURRENCE">stopping</EVENT> short, as though by instinct, at the threshold of any dangerous thought. It includes the power of not grasping analogies, of <EVENT eid="e18" class="I_ACTION">failing</EVENT> to <EVENT eid="e19" class="OCCURRENCE">perceive</EVENT> logical errors, of <EVENT eid="e20" class="OCCURRENCE">misunderstanding</EVENT> the simplest arguments Crimestop, in short, means protective stupidity. 
 
Power is in <EVENT eid="e21" class="OCCURRENCE">tearing</EVENT> human minds to pieces and <EVENT eid="e22" class="OCCURRENCE">putting</EVENT> them together again in new shapes of your own choosing. 
 
It Cant Happen Here, a <TIMEX3 tid="t7" type="DATE" value="1935">1935</TIMEX3> dystopian novel by Sinclair Lewis, <EVENT eid="e23" class="OCCURRENCE">hit</EVENT> No. 7 on Amazons Bestseller list as of <TIMEX3 tid="t8" type="DATE" value="2017-01-25">Wednesday</TIMEX3> night (the list is updated hourly.) 
 
The pre-World War II semi-satirical political novel by the Pulitzer Prize winning author is, <EVENT eid="e24" class="REPORTING">according</EVENT> to the publishers synopsis, a cautionary tale about the fragility of democracy, it is an alarming, eerily timeless look at how fascism could <EVENT eid="e25" class="OCCURRENCE">take</EVENT> hold in America. 
 
Hitting No. 9 that night was a book written <TIMEX3 tid="t9" type="DATE" value="1931">86 years ago</TIMEX3>: Aldous Huxleys <TIMEX3 tid="t10" type="DATE" value="1931">1931</TIMEX3> novel, Brave New World. 
 
In Huxleys dystopia, <EVENT eid="e26" class="OCCURRENCE">set</EVENT> in London in <TIMEX3 tid="t11" type="DATE" value="2540">the year 2540</TIMEX3>, or 632 A.F., After Ford, humans are <EVENT eid="e27" class="OCCURRENCE">created</EVENT> and <EVENT eid="e28" class="OCCURRENCE">conditioned according</EVENT> to the society's strict caste system, life has been almost entirely <EVENT eid="e29" class="I_STATE">industrialized</EVENT> to <EVENT eid="e30" class="OCCURRENCE">create</EVENT> consumers, and is <EVENT eid="e31" class="OCCURRENCE">controlled</EVENT> by a few people at the top of a World State. 
 
Ray Bradburys dystopian Fahrenheit 451  a bleak future where television rules, books are <EVENT eid="e32" class="OCCURRENCE">burned</EVENT> and literature is on the brink of extinction  <EVENT eid="e33" class="OCCURRENCE">hit</EVENT> number 17 on that list on <TIMEX3 tid="t12" type="TIME" value="2017-01-25TNI">Wednesday night</TIMEX3>. 
 
At No. 27, Margaret Atwoods dystopian The Handmaids Tale, about a future where women are second class citizens, valued only as reproductive units to <EVENT eid="e34" class="OCCURRENCE">create</EVENT> babies, and are barred from reading. 
 
I wont <EVENT eid="e35" class="OCCURRENCE">go</EVENT> into the hows and whys. Hey, maybe a whole lot of English teachers <EVENT eid="e36" class="OCCURRENCE">assigned</EVENT> dystopian novels <TIMEX3 tid="t13" type="DATE" value="2017-W04">last week</TIMEX3>. And after all, this is only one sites list. 
 
Ill just <EVENT eid="e37" class="REPORTING">say</EVENT> that when the winds of change shift, we <EVENT eid="e38" class="OCCURRENCE">fall</EVENT> back into art, words, music, poetry. We <EVENT eid="e39" class="STATE">fall</EVENT> back on writers. Have since the dawn of the written word. Before that, we <EVENT eid="e40" class="I_ACTION">looked</EVENT> to <EVENT eid="e41" class="OCCURRENCE">fire</EVENT> and drumbeat, cave paintings of animal fat and pigment smeared on rock walls. 
 
We <EVENT eid="e42" class="OCCURRENCE">look</EVENT> to ideas, to words, because we <EVENT eid="e43" class="I_STATE">need</EVENT> to <EVENT eid="e44" class="OCCURRENCE">look</EVENT> to something that feels permanent and real. We look to ink, <EVENT eid="e45" class="OCCURRENCE">formed</EVENT> into shapes, stamped onto wood and pulp. We hold them in our hands. Or we see them on a screen, <EVENT eid="e46" class="OCCURRENCE">illuminated</EVENT>, glowing, black and white sculptures that fire neurons inside our skulls. 
 
Optic fibers <EVENT eid="e47" class="OCCURRENCE">translating</EVENT> some code, something ancient, into cells, into strands of fiber and carbon. Synapses, nerve endings <EVENT eid="e48" class="OCCURRENCE">pulsing</EVENT> inside casement of bone. Blood <EVENT eid="e49" class="REPORTING">flows</EVENT>, pulses quickens. Breath changes. Something is <EVENT eid="e50" class="OCCURRENCE">released</EVENT>. Something is <EVENT eid="e51" class="OCCURRENCE">eased</EVENT>. 
 
Orwell <EVENT eid="e52" class="OCCURRENCE">died</EVENT> in <TIMEX3 tid="t14" type="DATE" value="1950">1950</TIMEX3>. <TIMEX3 tid="t15" type="DATE" value="2017-W05">This week</TIMEX3>, droves of people <EVENT eid="e53" class="OCCURRENCE">bought</EVENT> his book. So maybe this passage is the truest thing he ever <EVENT eid="e54" class="OCCURRENCE">wrote</EVENT>: 
 
We are the dead. Our only true life is in the future. We shall <EVENT eid="e55" class="OCCURRENCE">take</EVENT> part in it as handfuls of dust and splinters of boneWe can only <EVENT eid="e56" class="OCCURRENCE">spread</EVENT> our knowledge outwards from individual to individual, generation after generation there is no other way. 
 
Lauren Daley is a book columnist and freelance writer. Contact her at ldaley33@gmail.com.
</TEXT>


